{{merge|close, but no cigar}}
==English==
===Etymology===
The phrase probably originates from contests at fairs or carnivals where the prize was a [[cigar]].

===Expression===
'''[[close]] [[but]] [[no]] [[cigar]]'''
#{{idiom}} Used to indicate that a [[guess]] or [[attempt]] was good, or close, but not correct.  The implication is that a miss, no matter how close it was, is still a miss, and in reality no better than any other miss.
#:'''''Close, but no cigar.''' Actually, it was a trick question, and he never went to Spain at all.''

